SIMPLE: instinctive
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Instinctive
<hw>In*stinc"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>instinctif</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to instinct; derived
from, or prompted by, instinct; of the nature of instinct; determined by
natural impulse or propensity; acting or produced without reasoning,
deliberation, instruction, or experience; spontaneous.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Instinctive</xex> motion.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Instinctive</xex> dread.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With taste <qex>instinctive</qex> give⟦br⟧
Each grace appropriate.</q> <rj><qau>Mason.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have we had <qex>instinctive</qex> intimations of the death of
some absent friends?</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The terms <xex>instinctive belief</xex>,
<xex>instinctive judgment</xex>, <xex>instinctive cognition</xex>, are
expressions not ill adapted to characterize a belief, judgment, or
cognition, which, as the result of no anterior consciousness, is, like
the products of animal instinct, the intelligent effect of (as far as we
are concerned) an unknown cause.</note> <rj><au>Sir H.
Hamilton.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Natural; voluntary; spontaneous; original;
innate; inherent; automatic.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instinctively</ent>⟦br⟧
